@Node "Intro" "Introduction"
@Prev "Main"
@Next "Usage"

@{bd "Introduction"}

When @{"LhA" link LhA} came along, Amiga users were able to store files in one (generally)
smaller  file - an @{b}LhA@{ub} @{"archive" link Arc} . Then @{"LZX" link LZX} came along - allowing much better
compression  rates  for  some  files,  so  much  more  space could be saved.
	When I first got  @{b}LZX@{ub}  I found it a lot of work converting  my old  @{b}LhA@{ub}
archives  to  the new @{b}LZX@{ub} format via the @{"CLI" link CLI}, and sometimes found that after
doing it that my original @{b}LhA@{ub} files were smaller than the new @{b}LZX@{ub} ones! Thus
@{bl "LhA2LZX"} was born. This script file allows the user to convert their archives
from  @{b}LhA@{ub}  to  @{b}LZX@{ub}  or  vice  versa,  or alternatively it will intelligently
convert  the  archive  to  the smallest format! It is all done by requesters
 - so the user doesn't even need to touch the keyboard!

What  makes it useful is that this program is an @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} @{"script" link Scripts} file, which
means  you can load it into a text viewer/editor and see how it all works. I
have  commented  many  of the lines to help the user understand more what is
happening,  and to help in case you want to write your own front-ends to @{b}CLI@{ub}
programs, or to perform certain actions.

@Endnode

@Node "Usage" "How to use LhA2LZX"
@Prev "Intro"
@Next "Reqs"

@{bd "Usage"}

- @{b}Double-click@{ub} on the @{"LhA2LZX_v2.7" SYSTEM "run LhA2LZX_v2.7"} icon
- @{b}Select@{ub} the @{b}FULL PATH@{ub} of the  directory that your  original @{b}archive@{ub} is in
- @{b}Select@{ub} the @{b}archive@{ub}
- Choose where a @{b}temporary directory@{ub} should be made (to store the files of
	the archive whilst @{b}de-archiving@{ub}).  There should be at least @{b}3-4@{ub} times
	the size of the original archive here
- Choose whether to convert to the @{b}other@{ub}  archive type (i.e. @{b}LhA to LZX@{ub} or
	@{b}LZX to LhA@{ub}) or simply to the @{b}smallest@{ub} archive
- @{bl "LhA2LZX"} will @{b}convert and save@{ub} the  new archive @{b}in  place of the original@{ub}


- @{bl "LhA2LZX"} can be run from the @{b}CLI@{ub} by simply typing

		@{fg shine}execute <path>/LhA2LZX_v2.7@{fg text}

  	where <path> is the path of the directory it is in.

@Endnode

@Node "Reqs" "Requirements - What you need to run LhA2LZX"
@Prev "Usage"
@Next "Scripts"

@{bd "Requirements"}

@{bl "LhA2LZX"} requires several things to work:
@{i}[	BaseName				(1.3, arp component)		] @{ui}
	CD					(1.3 in C:, 2.x/3.x internal)
	Copy					(1.3/2.x/3.x in C:)
	Delete				(1.3/2.x/3.x in C:)
	Echo					(1.3 in C:, 2.x/3.x internal)
	Else					(1.3 in C:, 2.x/3.x internal)
	Endif				(1.3 in C:, 2.x/3.x internal)
	Eval					(1.3/2.x/3.x in C:)
	If					(1.3 in C:, 2.x/3.x internal)
	Lab					(1.3/2.x/3.x in C:)
	List					(1.3/2.x/3.x in C:)
	MakeDir				(1.3/2.x/3.x in C:)
	Quit					(1.3 in C:, 2.x/3.x internal)
	RequestChoice 			(3.x only, located in C:)
	RequestFile 			(3.x only, located in C:)
	Resident				(1.3 in C:, 2.x/3.x internal)
	Skip					(1.3 in C:, 2.x/3.x internal)
	Which				(1.3/2.x/3.x in C:)

Both the @{"LhA" link LhA} and @{"LZX" link LZX} tools will also be needed - preferably in @{b}C:@{ub}
 @{i}[these are both available on the AmiNET, and from most PD libraries] @{ui}

@{b}LhA@{ub} can be found at util/arc/LhA_e138.run and @{b}LZX@{ub} is at util/arc/lzx121r1.lha
Since @{"v2.6" link Hist 154} the registered version of @{b}LZX@{ub} is needed - and the registered
keyfile is now freely available and part of the @{b}LZX@{ub} distribution.

@{b}IconX@{ub} will also be needed in @{b}C:@{ub} if you want to double-click the icon to
start @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.

From @{"v2.3" link Hist 113}+ of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}, @{b}BaseName@{ub} is no longer used.

Versions of @{"RequestChoice" link ReqC} & @{"RequestFile" link ReqF} for @{b}2.x@{ub} are available on the @{b}AmiNET@{ub}.

@{b}Tested on:@{ub}

A1200, 25Mhz '020 + FPU (Apollo Turbo 1220), 170 MB HD, 2/4 MB RAM
A1200, 25Mhz '030 + FPU (Blizzard), 580 MB HD, 2/4 MB RAM

@{b}Untested@{ub} on @{b}KS 1.x/2.x@{ub}.
If you can test it on any of these, please mail me with the results :^)

@Endnode

@Node "Scripts" "Creating AmigaDOS Scripts"
@Prev "Reqs"
@Next "Bugs"

@{bd "Creating AmigaDos Scripts"}							@{" Read LhA2LZX " Link LhA2LZX_v2.7/Main}

@{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}  scripts are very useful because everyone who has @{b}Workbench@{ub} has the
necessary  software  to  write them. They are written in a language which is
easy to learn and easy to understand, and can be used to do many things. The
@{b}startup-sequence@{ub}  is  the  most  well known of these scripts, and shows just
what  they  can do. Programs can be called and started, and @{"arguments" link Args} can be
passed  to  them,  which  is essentially how @{bl "LhA2LZX"} works - @{"LhA" link LhA} and @{"LZX" link LZX} are
called  from the @{bl "LhA2LZX"} script and the arguments that the user has selected
are  passed  to  them.  An  important  aspect  of  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  is  the  use  of
@{"Environment Variables" link Env}.

Scripts  are written using a text editor (such as @{b}Ed@{ub}), and do not need to be
compiled,  so  you  can  simply run them from @{b}Workbench@{ub} or the @{"CLI" link CLI} (which is
great  when  you're writing  them - just the click of a button to test it!).

Comments  (anything  written  after  a  semi-colon "@{b};@{ub}") are ignored when the
script  is  running,  so don't be afraid to comment your file so you clearly
know  what  bit  does  what. They will not affect the actions of the script.

If  you  do not have an @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} manual,  detailing what all the keywords do
(there  wasn't  one  in the @{b}A1200@{ub} distribution), there are many available in
the @{b}Public Domain@{ub} - the one I use is the fantastic @{"DOSMan" link WhatUse 20} by @{b}Peter Bagnato@{ub}
which  details  the  usage  of  commands  up to and including the new @{b}WB 3.1@{ub}
ones,  and  gives  examples of how to use them. Also get your hands on other
script  files  such  as the  other ones I have done @{" " link Also}, or @{"DiskSqueeze" link WhatUse 12}, a @{b}DMS@{ub}
alternative that crunches entire disks with @{b}LZX@{ub}! That file helped greatly in
creating @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.

@Endnode

@Node "Args" "Arguments"

@{bd "Arguments"}

Arguments are the keywords  that follow  the program's name  if started from
the @{"CLI" link CLI},and tell the program (for example) which file(s) to use, any special
command or options to use and so on.

For example, if you typed

	@{fg shine}LZX ?@{fg text}

in a CLI, you would get a list of the arguments you can use:

	@{fg fill}LZX [-<options>] <command> <archive> [<file>...] [<destdir>]@{fg text}

where @{b}options@{ub} are any options (such as make filenames uppercase)
      @{b}command@{ub} is what action you are performing (e.g. archiving)
      @{b}archive@{ub} is the name of the archive e.g. to be saved
      @{b}file@{ub} is the name(s) of the file(s) to be e.g. archived
      @{b}destdir@{ub} is the name of the destination directory where the archive  is
                                                           e.g. to be saved.

@{fg shine}e.g.@{fg text}
	if you typed at a CLI

		@{fg shine}LZX -F a Test.lzx dh0:Games/#? dh1:@{fg text}

	you would be archiving all (@{b}#?@{ub}) the files in the @{fg shine}dh0:Games/@{fg text} directory,
	with a @{b}F@{ub}ast  progress display  (-F) and the  archive would  be saved as
	@{b}Test.lzx@{ub} in the @{fg shine}dh1:@{fg text} directory.

@Endnode

@Node "Env" "Environment Variables"

@{bd "Environment Variables"}

@{i}Note: in the following examples I have missed off the prefix "nl2z" of
each variable so that it is easier to read, as of @{"v2.6a" link Hist 163}@{ui}

Environment  Variables  are exceedingly useful in script files as they allow
numbers  or  text  to be saved to a small file in @{b}ENV:@{ub} (in @{b}RAM:@{ub}) and used by
any program. What makes them so useful is that if a dollar sign ($) preceeds
the  filename  when it is called, the contents of the file are used instead.
So  if  for  instance the text @{fg shine}dh0:Games/@{fg text} was saved as the file @{b}ENV:zxc@{ub}, and
you typed

	@{fg shine}cd $zxc@{fg text}

in a CLI, the current directory  would change to @{b}dh0:Games/@{ub} - just as if you
had typed

	@{fg shine}cd dh0:Games/@{fg text}

Here is a relevant part of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} that shows this:
@{JRIGHT}@{"Click to find in LhA2LZX" LINK "LhA2LZX_v2.7/MAIN" 188}
@{JLEFT}@{fg shine}if $suf EQ lha@{fg text}
	@{fg shine}cd $drw1
	cd l2z
	$wlha x -a -F -M -x $ldfl@{fg text}

Previously in the script, @{b}List@{ub} was used (found in @{b}C:@{ub}) to get the suffix (all
the  letters  after  the final full stop in the filename) of the filename to
determine  if  it was an @{b}LhA@{ub} or @{b}LZX@{ub} archive, and the suffix was saved as the
file  @{b}ENV:suf@{ub}.  So if the file is an @{b}LhA@{ub} archive, the line would be the same
as  "@{fg shine}if  lha  EQUALS  lha@{fg text}".  It  would then @{b}cd@{ub} to the directory the user had
chosen to put the temporary  storage directory @{b}l2z@{ub},  and would then @{b}cd@{ub}  into
@{b}l2z@{ub} itself.Next it would call @{b}LhA@{ub}(with the location of the @{b}LhA@{ub} program saved
as the file @{b}ENV:wlha@{ub}) and e@{b}x@{ub}tract all the files, preserving their @{b}a@{ub}ttributes
(-a)  from  the  chosen  archive  (the  filename  of the archive is saved as
@{b}ENV:ldfl@{ub}), with a  @{b}F@{ub}ast progress display (-F), preserving the path names(-x)
with  no  "autoshow"  files (which automatically display themselves when @{b}LhA@{ub}
de-/archives  them). So if  @{b}LhA@{ub}  was  in  @{b}C:@{ub}  and  the  archive  was  called
@{fg shine}dh1:Test.lha@{fg text}(which would have been selected by the user via a requester),the
final line would be the same as

	@{fg shine}C:LhA x -a -F -M -x dh1:Test.lha@{fg text}

Environment Variables can be used also to store numbers:
@{JRIGHT}@{"Click to find in LhA2LZX" LINK "LhA2LZX_v2.7/MAIN" 140}
@{JLEFT}	@{fg shine}eval >env:flmem $flsz * 4@{fg text}
@{JRIGHT}@{"More info" link Hist 107}
@{JLEFT}This  line  calls  @{b}Eval@{ub}  (in  @{b}C:@{ub}),  and tells it to multiply the size of the
original  archive  (found with @{b}List@{ub} and saved as @{b}ENV:flsz@{ub}) by 4, and to save
the  answer  as  @{b}ENV:flmem@{ub} instead of printing it to screen. This is used in
@{bl "LhA2LZX"}  to determine if the user's machine has enough memory to perform the
action  of de-/archiving (@{b}LZX@{ub} archives can de-archive sometimes to 3-4 times
the  size  of the archive) if they have chosen @{b}RAM:@{ub} to temporarily store the
files  of  the archive, and warns them if there may be insufficient memory -
note  here  that file redirection is used (the @{b}>@{ub} sign), which enables user's
choices to be saved in files rather than be printed to the screen.

@{b}When  creating  your own script files, it is a sound idea for the very first
line to be

	@{fg shine}set echo on@{fg text}

as  this  will give a display of all the actions being performed, so you can
see exactly what is happening and where things need to be changed to fix any
problems.  This  can  be  deleted when the script is finished and everything
works  as  you  would  want  it  to.@{ub}

@Endnode

@Node "Bugs" "Bugs in LhA2LZX"
@Prev "Scripts"
@Next "Hist"

@{bd "Problems"}

Apparently the @{b}clear screen@{ub} command (@{b}echo@{ub} "@{fg shine}*ec@{fg text}") doesn't work for @{b}KS 2.0@{ub}, so
I changed it back to "@{fg shine}*e[1;1H*eJ@{fg text}" in @{"v2.6a" link Hist 163} (this moves the cursor to  @{b}column
1 row 1@{ub} and @{b}clears@{ub} all that follows it).

When @{b}de-archiving@{ub}, if it encounters an empty  directory, @{b}LZX@{ub} may  display the
error message

	@{fg shine}*** LZX: Error writing to disk; disk full?@{fg text}

but still continues to @{b}de-archive@{ub} regardless. This seems to be a bug in @{b}LZX@{ub},
and seems to have  no effect on the process.  When the files are @{b}archived@{ub} by
@{b}LhA@{ub}  seconds  later,  the  empty  directories  are  also @{b}archived@{ub} as normal.

@{b}e.g.@{ub}	Here is a copy of the output from one of my tests:
@{LINDENT 1}
@{fg fill}LZX 1.21 (Evaluation) Archive/Extract utility - 68020/68030 Version.
Copyright © 1995 Data Compression Technologies.  All rights reserved.
Commercial use of this unregistered program is prohibited.

Extracting files from archive 'AQ2:DiskSalv/Executive.lzx':
 (       0 /       0) executive_v2.10/empty/ (       0 /       0) executive
*** LZX: Error writing to disk; disk full?
 (       0 /       0) executive_v2.10/c/empty2/empty3/ (       0 /       0)
*** LZX: Error writing to disk; disk full?
  ** 30 file(s) extracted, all files OK

Operation successful

LhA Evaluation V1.51 - Copyright (c) 1992 by Stefan Boberg.     
All rights reserved. Not for commercial use.

Creating new archive 'Executive.lha':
	Frozen: ( 52.4%)    3604 =>   1713 : executive_v2.10/.Product-Info
	Archiving empty directory `executive_v2.10/c/empty2/empty3'
	Frozen: (  6.0%)    3576 =>   3360 : executive_v2.10/data/DashboardPrefs.l
	Stored: (  0.0%)   38661 =>  38661 : executive_v2.10/data/Register.lzx
	Archiving empty directory `executive_v2.10/empty'
30 files added, all files OK.

Operation successful.@{fg text}
@{LINDENT 0}
As can  be  seen  above,  the empty directories I added ("@{fg shine}c/empty2/empty3@{fg text}" &
"@{fg shine}empty@{fg text}") are still archived,so the message does not seem to affect anything.
For clarity,the disk was @{i}not@{ui} full.

Since having access to the AmiNET,  I have found an additional bug, and that
is AmigaDOS's and LZX's inability to handle tildes (~) in filenames. I found
this when copying files from the PC's here at University to my disks to take
back to my trusty  Amiga,  when if a filename is greater than  8  characters
long  (suffix not included), it is  truncated : so for  instance an  archive
called "@{b}longarcname.lha@{ub}" would be renamed "@{b}longar~1.lha@{ub}" when saved to disk.
When I tried to use these in  @{bl "LhA2LZX"},  LZX would not do anything with them,
but gave an output of @{fg fill}Operation successful@{fg text}.  I have tried getting round this
by detecting a tilde in  a  filename  and  getting  the  user to input a new
filename,  but AmigaDOS treats tilde's as something to do with negation - it
is used in pattern-matching. If you want to get a list of all the files in a
directory, you would type
@{fg fill}list #?@{fg text}
If you wanted a list of  all the files except for the icon files,  you would
type
@{fg fill}list ~(#?.info)@{fg text}
which would list all the files apart from those ending in info (icon files).
So it seems if an archive has a tilde in it's name,  AmigaDOS and LZX try to
operate on it in a pattern-matching context.
     Using the @{b}Type@{ub} command was the closest I got (e.g.
@{fg fill}Type FROM arc~2.lzx TO arc2.lzx@{fg text}
but the command only  copied part of  the file.  I tried also copy, join and
rename, but these didn't change the filename either.  The only way to change
the filename via the CLI would be to use the apostrophe (') before the tilde
e.g. if your archive was called my~arc.lzx:
@{fg fill}Rename my'~arc.lzx TO myarc.lzx@{fg text}
I don't think it's possible to insert characters like this via a script  :^(

Thanks to @{"Frank Bunton" link Thanks} for the help here.


This AmigaGuide has been tested only on WB3.1, so it is possible not all  of
the keywords will work under 3.0 or below systems.  If anyone can read  this
on  any other WB version,  please contact me  (you can load this into a text
viewer and read what all the missing words, if any, are. If all is not well,
I will change it.

@{b}Bug reports@{ub} and @{b}suggestions of improvement@{ub} are welcome.

Feel free to try out the @{i}first versions @{ui}of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} (i.e. 1.x),  but only use
copies  of  your  archives  as they have bugs in - hence you can see where I
improved it...  :^)

@Endnode

@Node "Hist" "Program History & Development"
@Prev "Bugs"
@Next "Fut"

@{bd "Program History"}

Versions @{b}1.1@{ub}, @{b}1.2@{ub}, @{"2.0" link Hist 36} - @{"2.7" link Hist 173}  are included in this  distribution so  you can
see how it developed.  Files are commented from @{b}2.0+@{ub}.

Version No.
~~~~~~~~~~~
@{h "1.0"}	Initial release

@{h "1.1"}	Added filesize difference to show which archive  was smallest

@{h "1.2"}	Fixed  bug  of  '@{b}l2z@{ub}' not  being  deleted if  the original archive  was
	smaller. Following extract is from original docs:

	"- DO NOT QUIT WHEN DE-ARCHIVING  otherwise  ONLY  THE  FILES CURRENTLY
	DE-ARCHIVED WILL BE PLACED IN THE NEW ARCHIVE. The new archive will not
	contain all the original files and will overwrite the ORIGINAL archive.

	So DON'T DO IT!

	This happens  because it  is an @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} @{"script" link Scripts} file,  and will perform
	the next  action @{b}immediately@{ub} after completing the previous one. Thus if
	it is @{b}de-archiving@{ub}  and it is  interrupted by a @{b}CTRL-C@{ub}, it will perform
	the next  action of  @{b}archiving@{ub} everything it has (so far) @{b}de-archived@{ub}."

	I  found  that  if  I  aborted  either @{b}LhA@{ub}  or  @{b}LZX@{ub}  whilst  they  were
	@{b}de-/archiving@{ub} then some of the original files were lost and, due to the
	nature of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}'s  workings, were  @{b}irretrievable@{ub}  unless a backup was
	kept. @{bl "LhA2LZX"} was  such that after it had @{b}de-archived@{ub} and @{b}archived@{ub}, the
	new file would  replace the old, so files would be lost if this process
	was interrupted - some of the original files would not be  @{b}archived@{ub} and
	then the new would replace the old. Not a good thing. This was fixed in
	@{"v2.1" link Hist 66}.

@{h "2.0"}	Added the extra option to convert to the other filetype.  This was done
	for 2 main reasons.  Firstly in  case the user merely wished to convert
	between the filetypes, and secondly so I could convert my @{b}.lzx@{ub} files to
	@{b}.lha@{ub},allowing me to enter them @{b}interactively@{ub} via @{b}DOpus5@{ub} and add to them
	- my version of @{b}LZXDir 26.6.95 v1.1 (modified by Stone-D)@{ub} doesn't allow
	me to add to @{b}.lzx@{ub} files @{b}interactively@{ub}.

	@{bd "Note"}
	@{b}Directory Opus@{ub} is a @{b}filemanager@{ub} which allows  you to quickly and easily
	perform actions on files.  @{b}LhADir@{ub} & @{b}LZXDir@{ub}  are two add-ons ("@{b}modules@{ub}")
	which  allow  you to  enter an @{b}.lha@{ub}/@{b}.lzx@{ub}  file as  if it were a  normal
	@{b}directory@{ub}  and perform  actions on the  files  within,  @{b}e.g.@{ub} viewing  a
	picture, as well as @{b}deleting@{ub} and @{b}adding@{ub}  files to the @{b}archive@{ub} as if you
	were merely transferring files from one directory to another. If I want
	to add a file to  an @{b}.lzx@{ub} archive  however I  have to convert  it to an
	@{b}.lha@{ub} archive due to the version I have.If anyone has an updated version
	of @{b}LZXDir@{ub}, please feel free to send it to me.

	This  version of @{bl "LhA2LZX"} also checked  if the file was  already of  the
	type that the user wished to convert to.

@{h "2.1"}	Added routines to check if the @{b}FULL@{ub} path of the @{b}archive@{ub} was chosen from
	the file requester by checking the  size of the path name. Also did the
	same to check that a file had been chosen.Altered the "@{b}Convert to. . ?@{ub}"
	routine  to @{b}automatically@{ub} check  the filetype as this made  things more
	logical (previously you could try to convert an @{b}.lha@{ub} archive to an @{b}.lha@{ub}
	archive . . .), and also saved me from trying to remember what type I'd
	just converted  the file to.  The routine allowing the checking of  the
	filetype  was already being  used in @{bl "LhA2LZX"},  so it was  really just a
	cut-&-paste job once I'd realised it.

	@{b}* MAJOR BUG FIX *@{ub}
	Stumbled  across the  means to add @{b}error  detection@{ub} if  something  went
	wrong in the @{b}de-/archiving@{ub} process! @{b}@{i}BIG@{ub}@{ui} thanks to @{b}Peter Bagnato@{ub} and his
	@{"DOSMan" link WhatUse 20}  creation  -  an  @{b}AmigaGuide@{ub}  detailing  the usage  of  @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}
	commands, with examples  -  which is a boon to those of us that haven't
	got  an  @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}  reference  manual.  Fixing  this  bug meant  that if
	anything  went  wrong when  @{b}de-/archiving@{ub}  (such as a  @{b}user  abort@{ub} or a
	@{b}corrupt file@{ub}), then @{bl "LhA2LZX"} would stop immediately and so all archives,
	the new and the original, would remain intact. And all by adding only 6
	lines of code . . . I could now sleep at night.

@{h "2.2"}	Deleted all the 'deletes' at  the start of  the file  as I decided that
	they were unnecessary. If @{bl "LhA2LZX"} had been quitted and then re-started,
	the @{b}env:@{ub} files  would  have already been  deleted when  it was quit the
	first time. If it was being started for the first time, chances are the
	files wouldn't be there anyway as @{b}env:@{ub} is a temporary directory in @{b}RAM:@{ub}
	and therefore erased with each reset. If the user chose to convert more
	archives(the final requester of the program), then the @{b}env:@{ub} files would
	be overwritten with the new variables. This also allowed me to  use the
	@{b}directory@{ub} of the @{b}last archive chosen@{ub}  as the @{b}default path@{ub}  for the next
	archive  - something I had wanted to do from the start - as it saves on
	searching  through all of  your  directories if you have  a drawer with
	several archives in which you wish to convert.

	I also changed the new  archive copying routine to copy the new archive
	to the selected destination @{b}BEFORE@{ub} deleting the old in case of mishaps,
	but  then altered  it back for two reasons  -  there  may not be enough
	space  in the  destination, especially  if  it is a floppy,  to contain
	both the archives  (new & old) before  the old is  deleted, and also it
	would now make little difference as this part of the script would never
	be reached  if something  @{b}DID@{ub}  go wrong  when it was @{b}de-/archiving@{ub}, now
	that the @{b}error detection@{ub} was in place.

	The "@{b}Convert to . . ?@{ub}" requester was  changed  to show the  filename in
	the title bar. The output messages detailing  which archive is  smaller
	were put into requesters to lessen the output in the CLI window - but I
	had to sacrifice the @{b}ANSI@{ub} colouring to do this. Now the only @{b}CLI@{ub} output
	to screen  is the coloured  closing message,  which is displayed whilst
	all the temporary files created are deleted.

	@{b}Amount of free memory is checked@{ub}  if the '@{b}l2z@{ub}' is selected in @{b}RAM:@{ub},  to
	make sure you won't run out,  and a  requester pops  up advising you if
	this might happen. I would also like to  find the amount  of free space
	of  the  destination  directory (in case @{b}RAM:@{ub} isn't chosen) to  see  if
	there is  enough, but  I haven't yet  found a way  to do this using the
	@{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} files in the @{b}Workbench@{ub} distribution.

@{h "2.3"}	@{b}BaseName@{ub} now is no  longer used, as a function of @{b}List@{ub} is used instead,
	to give the filename without a suffix and the suffix on its own.Deleted
	a couple of deletions of environment variables as they were overwritten
	on the following line, and so  were unnecessary.  Added a small routine
	just to check that the archive name @{i}does@{ui} have an @{b}lzx/lha/lzh@{ub} suffix(@{b}lzh@{ub}
	is  @{b}de-archived@{ub}  by @{b}LhA@{ub}).  Added  detection  to  check  firstly if  the
	alternate  path  for  '@{b}l2z@{ub}'  exists  and secondly that it  is the  full
	pathname.

@{h "2.4"}	@{b}LZH@{ub} archives now  processed fully as if they  were normal @{b}LhA@{ub} archives.
	Found  a much nicer  line to  clear  the screen for the final  @{b}Thankyou@{ub}
	message ( from an old Amiga Power coverdisk!).  Extra options  added to
	the @{b}LhA/LZX@{ub} command line to give @{b}faster progress display@{ub} and @{b}suffixing@{ub}.
	Added extra @{b}ANSI@{ub} line "@{fg shine}*e[0 p@{fg text}" which supposedly turns off the cursor to
	make text output twice as fast, so @{b}LZX@{ub} etc. can now work faster.  Empty
	directories  now dealt with  and @{b}de/-archived@{ub} as usual,  although there
	seems to be a @{"bug" link Bugs 19} in @{b}LZX@{ub} here -  luckily this seems to in no way affect
	the running of @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.

	Also added a similar routine to that of the default path of the archive
	when using @{bl "LhA2LZX"} for multiple  archives (see @{"v2.2" link Hist 78})  to have a default
	path for where '@{b}l2z@{ub}' is stored, in case the user doesn't have much @{b}RAM:@{ub}
	(and so won't want to go  searching through drawers each time they want
	to have '@{b}l2z@{ub}' somewhere on their hard-drive).

@{h "2.5"}	Added 2 small routines just to check that both the @{b}path@{ub} and the @{b}archive@{ub}
	exist when selected,  in case the user decides to @{b}type in@{ub} either.  Also
	improved the "@{b}Convert to . . ?@{ub}"requester to show @{i}exactly @{ui} what filetype
	you are  converting and what you  can convert it to.  This makes things
	much  easier  to see  (in terms  of options),  and  also shows  off the
	ability of @{b}filetype detection@{ub} more.

	Also fixed  a small  bug in  the  @{b}Insufficient Memory@{ub}  area to do  with
	quotes and volume names with spaces in, such as @{fg shine}RamDisk:@{fg text}. Filenames or
	volume names with spaces need to be surrounded by quotation marks, like
	this:
		"@{fg shine}Ram Disk:@{fg text}"
	so they can be accessed -if you just type @{fg shine}Ram Disk:@{fg text} in a Shell,AmigaDOS
	will try to  run the command @{fg fill}Ram@{fg text}.  Now the path name of the archive can
	have spaces in.

@{h "2.6"}	@{b}First official release@{ub} (on my web page)
	As the  keyfile  for @{b}LZX@{ub} is now  freely available on the @{b}AmiNET@{ub},  extra
	features of @{b}LZX@{ub} are enabled, such as de-archiving of @{b}LhA/LZX@{ub} files,with
	a @{b}25-30%@{ub} speed increase.  Also is the option of faster archiving at the
	cost of 32k of RAM. I have included both of these here to  increase the
	overall  speed of  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.  I tried here to  fix the tilde  @{"bug" link Bugs 48},  but
	without much success.  Expect better handling in the next release!

@{h "2.6a"}	@{b}First AmiNET upload@{ub}
	All I did here was shorten  the length of the  program by renaming  the
	variables with the prefix "nl2z",  which is unique enough for me to use
	@{fg shine}list@{fg text} to generate a list of the  variables at the end and use this in  a
	script created by  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  to delete them all.   I got this idea  from
	reading  the  startup-sequence  (it uses  the same  principle  but runs
	monitor drivers).  I also changed  the command that  clears the  output
	screen at the end to make sure it will work on KS2.0.

@{h "2.7"}	This version now contains filename error trapping,  and fixes the tilde
	bug for  the moment.  If a tilde is detected in the filename,  an error
	message is  produced and  the program quits.  I am currently  trying to
	think of a way round this without quitting the program or have the user
	typing an  apostrophe before  the tilde themselves,  but I really don't
	know  of a way to get  AmigaDOS to scan filenames and insert  specified
	characters before other characters :^( , and I don't really want to use
	AREXX  or an actual  program to do this as  @{bl "LhA2LZX"}  is not just a file
	conversion utility, it is an exercise in AmigaDOS,showing its potential
	and all  that it can do.

	@{bl "LhA2LZX"} now skips to the  end and deletes all  variables currently made
	if @{b}LhA@{ub} or @{b}LZX@{ub} cannot be found, instead of just quitting.

	As the @{b}registered@{ub} version of @{b}LZX@{ub} is now needed,  a quick check is  now
	performed to see if the @{b}lzx.keyfile@{ub} exists,as otherwise LZX won't work.
@Endnode

@Node "Fut" "For the Future"
@Prev "Hist"
@Next "Legal"

@{bd "For the Future"}

	- Even safer archive handling by keeping backups.
	- New routines to copy multiple archives from floppy disk to hard
		  drive, and copy the individual archives back after processing.
	- New routines to check new archive sizes to see whether they will
		  fit nicely back on floppy.
	- Greater error trapping and handling, resulting in alternative
		  directories being chosen to store the new archive
	- Better handling of the @{"tilde bug" link Bugs 48} .

@{bd "What I would like..."}

...if anyone can help:

-A  small  program to get the space available on a disk and output only this
@{LINDENT 1} (preferably using it's Filesystem, in case it's using something like PFS and
the  diskspare.device...).  This  will allow me to tell the user information
such as  if the new  archive will  definitely fit on their floppy,  how much
space is left and so on)
@{LINDENT 0}
-Anything else you think might be useful to me... #&^)

@EndNode

