@Node "Also" "Also by the Author"
@Prev "Author"
@Next "Index"

@{bd "Also by the Author"}

All the programs below are @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} @{"script" link Scripts} files created purely to show what
you can achieve,using the software you already have,to make your life easier.
Most of them are simply "front-end" programs to @{"CLI" link CLI} executables- so you just
click requesters instead of typing out @{b}CLI@{ub} commands like in @{bl "LhA2LZX"}.

@{h "AllowBad.req"}
	Do you have @{b}floppies@{ub} with  @{b}hard errors@{ub} on?  Do you find that you simply
	can't @{b}format@{ub} them or @{b}use them properly@{ub}? Then @{b}wipe@{ub} away your @{b}tears@{ub},  for
	@{b}AllowBad.req@{ub}  is  here!   A   simple  requester  interface  to  @{i}Mikolaj
	Calusinski's@{ui} @{b}AllowBad@{ub} means  you  too  can now live  with the  peace of
	mind that never again will you have a @{b}Bad Floppy! ®@{ub}
@{h "DMSMaker"}
	A fab little @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} script file  allowing you to use all the standard
	functions of the @{b}DiskMasher@{ub} System - including read, write, view, test,
	repack,  and even encrypt  your  @{b}DMS@{ub}  files with an invisible password!
@{h "DSQView"}
	A small file  which  finds the  filelist in a  @{"DiskSqueeze" link WhatUse 12}  archive and
	displays it.
@{h "FillDisk"}
	Helps fill disks to their maximum, using @{i}Torbjörn Hultén's@{ui} "@{b}Fill v2.0.@{ub}"
	Choose your files by requester, and  @{b}Fill@{ub}  calculates which combination
	of files to  use to fill the  disk to its maximum.  Useful for storage.
@{h "HappySearch"}
	I once had a  @{b}virus@{ub}  which adds itself  to every file you open,  and is
	recognisable by finding "@{b}Happy New Year 96!@{ub}" in your files. HappySearch
	will search specified files to see if you have the virus.
@{h "LhAMaker"}
	This creates @{b}LhA@{ub} archives from  specified input files,  via requesters.
@{h "UnLZXer"}
	This de-archives @{b}LZX@{ub} archives to a chosen destination.

@Endnode

@Node "Arc" "Archiving"
@Next "De-arc"
@Prev "Index"

@{bd "Archiving"}

@{b}Archiving@{ub}  means  to  backup  files. In the case of @{b}LhA@{ub} & @{b}LZX@{ub}, all the files
you  wish  to  backup  -@{i}store  a copy somewhere in case you need them in the
future  to, for example, replace lost data@{ui}- are merged into one @{b}archive@{ub} file
and  @{b}compressed@{ub}, so that in almost all cases the final @{b}archive@{ub} file takes up
less space than the files which were @{b}archived@{ub} did.

See also @{" De-archiving " link De-arc}

@{b}NB@{ub}	"De-/archiving" in this document refers to when @{bl "LhA2LZX"} @{b}de-archives@{ub} and
	then @{b}archives@{ub} an archive.
@Endnode

@Node "De-arc" "De-archiving"
@Next "CLI"
@Prev "Arc"

@{bd "De-archiving"}

@{b}De-archiving@{ub}  means  to  restore  files  from  a  backup  archive. Files are
@{b}decompressed@{ub} and separated back to individual files.

See also @{" Archiving " link Arc}
@Endnode

@Node "CLI" "The Command Line Interface"
@Next "LhA"
@Prev "De-arc"

@{bd "CLI"}

The  @{b}C@{ub}ommand  @{b}L@{ub}ine  @{b}I@{ub}nterface allows the user to communicate to the computer
via the keyboard. The @{b}Shell@{ub} is the Amiga's @{b}CLI@{ub}.
@Endnode

@Node "LhA" "LhA & LHZ"
@Next "LZX"
@Prev "CLI"

@{h "LhA"}  is  a  utility which allows you to @{b}compress@{ub} and @{"archive" link Arc} files. It was a
very  popular program for backup and distribution purposes (i.e. the @{b}AmiNET@{ub})
but  is now being surpassed in terms of @{b}decompression times@{ub} and @{b}archive size@{ub}
by @{"LZX" link LZX}.

@{b}LhA@{ub} archives can be compressed further.  If you archive all your files  into
an  LhA  archive  with  no  compression, then  archive  this  with LhA  with
compression,  you can often save  quite a lot  more space, although you will
have to de-archive it twice.  I have not included  this facility in LhA2LZX,
because the same does not work with LZX,and it would have no real indication
how many times the archive had been re-archived, and may get too  complex to
be useful.  But it's nice to know anyway :^)

@{h "LHZ"} is similar to @{b}LhA@{ub}  and files @{b}archived@{ub} with  this are @{b}de-archived@{ub} by @{b}LhA@{ub}.
@Endnode

@Node "LZX" "LZX"
@Next "ReqC"
@Prev "LhA"

@{h "LZX"} is a utility which allows you to @{b}compress@{ub} and @{"archive" link Arc} files with often a
great degree of @{b}compression@{ub}. It also @{b}decompresses@{ub} data faster than any other
popular  Amiga  program.  It  gives  greater @{b}compression@{ub} because it uses the
knowledge of previous files in the archive,using an ability to transparently
look  for similar @{b}compressible data@{ub} across @{b}multiple files@{ub} before adding them
to an archive.

See also @{" LhA/LZH " link LhA}
@Endnode

@Node "ReqC" "RequestChoice"
@Next "ReqF"
@Prev "LZX"

@{h "RequestChoice"}  brings up a requester in which the user is prompted to make a
choice. The  @{b}title-, body- and button-text@{ub} is configurable so that it may be
used in any  situation.  The value of the button pressed by the user is then
returned so that the relevant process is chosen.

See also @{" RequestFile " link ReqF}
@Endnode

@Node "ReqF" "RequestFile"
@Next "Index"
@Prev "ReqC"

@{h "RequestFile"}  brings up a  filerequester  in  which the  user is  prompted to
choose a file.  The @{b}title-@{ub} and @{b}button-text@{ub} is configurable so that it may be
used in any  situation. The chosen file name is then returned so that it may
be used later.

See also @{" RequestChoice " link ReqC}
@Endnode

